1. Rule-based era
The first AI systems were expert systems built from human-written rules.
They worked well in narrow, predictable settings, but they broke easily when inputs changed or became ambiguous.

2. Machine learning era
AI then shifted to statistical learning, where models learned patterns from examples instead of fixed rules. 
This reduced manual coding and made AI useful for search, ranking, prediction, and classification at scale.

3. Deep learning era
Deep learning made another jump by letting models learn features directly from raw data like images, 
speech, and text. That lowered the need for hand-engineered features and improved performance on complex tasks.

4. Foundation models
Foundation models are large, general-purpose models trained on huge and diverse datasets. 
They are pre-trained once, then adapted to many tasks with prompting or fine-tuning, 
which is why they are more flexible than earlier task-specific systems

__________________________________________________________________________________________________________

Rule-based AI: A thermostat that turns the heater on when the room is cold.

Machine learning AI: A spam filter that learns which emails are spam.

Deep learning AI: A phone that unlocks by recognizing your face.

Foundation model: ChatGPT, which can answer many different kinds of questions.

For your topic, the easiest way to remember it is:

Rules = fixed instructions.

Machine learning = learns from examples.

Deep learning = learns from lots of data.

Foundation model = a big general model that can do many tasks

